# LOTA EK manufacturer root sources.
#
# One line per trusted vendor root:
#
#   <sha256>  <filename>  <url>  <vendor label...>
#
#   sha256    lowercase hex SHA-256 over the certificate DER. Verify this
#             out of band against the vendor's published fingerprint before
#             trusting a root -- this pin is the whole point of the bundle.
#   filename  bare name the root is written under in the bundle directory.
#   url       distribution point the root is fetched from.
#   label     free text, for the manifest and diagnostics.
#
# lota-ek-roots-update.sh fetches each url, recomputes the DER SHA-256, and
# refuses to write any root whose fingerprint does not match the pin. Lines
# whose pin is still the REPLACE_ME placeholder are rejected, so an
# unverified vendor cannot slip into the bundle.
#
# Two honesty markers, both fail-closed:
#   REPLACE_ME  pin  -- no operator-verified fingerprint yet; the tool stops.
#   UNVERIFIED  url  -- no source I could confirm; replace it with the root
#                       your own platforms actually chain to.
#
# None of these URLs is authoritative on its own. The reliable way to find
# the right root for a platform is to take an actual EK certificate and walk
# its issuer chain to the self-signed root:
#
#   # discrete TPM / Intel PTT: EK cert lives in TPM NV
#   sudo tpm2_nvreadpublic                       # find the 0x01c0xxxx EK cert
#   sudo tpm2_nvread 0x01c00002 -o ek.der        # RSA EK (0x01c0000a = ECC)
#   openssl x509 -in ek.der -inform DER -noout -issuer -ext authorityInfoAccess
#   # Windows host: PowerShell (admin)
#   #   $ek = Get-TpmEndorsementKeyInfo -HashAlgorithm Sha256
#   #   $ek.ManufacturerCertificates + $ek.AdditionalCertificates
#   # follow each "CA Issuers" URL up until issuer == subject (the root),
#   # then: sha256sum root.der  -> the pin.
#
# Fill in only the vendors your fleet attests.

# Infineon publishes its OPTIGA TPM root via its own PKI host.
# Documented starting point. Confirm the fingerprint before trusting it.
REPLACE_ME  infineon-optiga-rsa-root.pem  https://pki.infineon.com/OptigaRsaRootCA/OptigaRsaRootCA.crt  Infineon OPTIGA TPM RSA Root CA

# Intel runs two EK PKIs: legacy discrete / early-PTT roots at
# upgrades.intel.com, and the Intel OnDie CA
# (https://tsci.intel.com/content/OnDieCA/) used by modern CSME firmware TPM
# (PTT) on Tiger Lake and later -- a CSME PTT EK cert has an issuer like
# "CSME <SoC> PTT" that chains up through OnDie CA, NOT the legacy root.
# The legacy URL below does not fit a CSME/PTT chain, so it is left UNVERIFIED:
# walk your EK cert's issuer up the OnDie CA repo to its self-signed root and
# record that URL + pin.
REPLACE_ME  intel-ek-root.pem             UNVERIFIED  Intel EK Root CA (legacy upgrades.intel.com) / Intel OnDie CA root (CSME PTT)

# STM publishes its TPM EK CA chain via GlobalSign (ST application note
# TN1330, "TPM EK certificate"). The line below pins the ST TPM Root.
# The chain's top root is GlobalSign Trusted Computing CA
# (https://secure.globalsign.com/cacert/gstpmroot.crt) -- pin whichever
# level your fleet's EK certificates terminate at.
REPLACE_ME  stm-tpm-ek-root.pem           https://secure.globalsign.com/cacert/stmtpmekroot.crt  STMicroelectronics TPM EK Root CA

# AMD fTPM and AMD-based vTPM EK certificates have no single stable public
# root distribution point: on most platforms they chain under Microsoft's
# TPM PKI rather than an AMD root, and many AMD fTPMs ship without an EK
# certificate provisioned in NV at all.
# There is nothing to pin until you have an actual EK cert whose chain
# you can walk, so both stay UNVERIFIED.
REPLACE_ME  amd-ftpm-ek-root.pem          UNVERIFIED  AMD fTPM EK Root CA
REPLACE_ME  microsoft-tpm-root.pem        UNVERIFIED  Microsoft TPM Root CA (covers AMD fTPM / vTPM EK chains)
